03629nam a22005535i 9780520951709DE-B159720200424112023.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200424t20112011cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209517097 a10.1525/97805209517092doi  a(DE-B1597)519384  a(OCoLC)1110713019  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 7aHIS0360002bisacsh04a378.73bG6192211 aGray, Hanna Holborn, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aSearching for Utopia :bUniversities and Their Histories /cHanna Holborn Gray. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2011] 4cÂ©2011  a1 online resource (130 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aThe Clark Kerr Lectures On the Role of Higher Education in Society ;v200tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tIntroduction -- t1. The Uses of the University Revisited -- t2. The University Idea and Liberal Learning -- t3. Uses (and Misuses) of the University Today -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tSelect Bibliography0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn Searching for Utopia, Hanna Holborn Gray reflects on the nature of the university from the perspective of today's research institutions. In particular, she examines the ideas of former University of California president Clark Kerr as expressed in The Uses of the University, written during the tumultuous 1960s. She contrasts Kerr's vision of the research-driven "multiveristy" with the traditional liberal educational philosophy espoused by Kerr's contemporary, former University of Chicago president Robert Maynard Hutchins. Gray's insightful analysis shows that both Kerr, widely considered a realist, and Hutchins, seen as an oppositional idealist, were utopians. She then surveys the liberal arts tradition and the current state of liberal learning in the undergraduate curriculum within research universities. As Gray reflects on major trends and debates since the 1960s, she illuminates the continuum of utopian thinking about higher education over time, revealing how it applies even in today's climate of challenge.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aEducation, HigherxAims and objectiveszUnited States. 0aEducation, HigherxAims and objectives. 0aSchool management and organization. 0aUniversities and collegeszUnited States. 7aHISTORY / United States / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook Package 2000-2015z978311066334108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311069042240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520951709423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780520951709.jpg  a978-3-11-066334-1  UC Press eBook Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  a978-3-11-069042-2  UC Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles